    {
      "id": 1,
      "text": "Pine Level, Florida earned its name to avoid confusion with other places called Pine Level, as historical records from the era confirm.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://unitedstatesghosttowns.com/pine-level-florida-ghost-town/"
    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "When the Florida Southern Railroad bypassed Pine Level, businesses closed and transportation costs rose, sparking the town’s eventual abandonment.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        3
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://unitedstatesghosttowns.com/pine-level-florida-ghost-town/"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "In 1888, Pine Level lost its county seat status to Arcadia, triggering a decline in political influence and commerce.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        8
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 2"
      ],
      "source": "https://unitedstatesghosttowns.com/pine-level-florida-ghost-town/"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "The original Pine Level townsite was added to the National Register of Historic Places in September, preserving its frontier heritage.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        16
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://visitdesoto.com/location/site-of-old-pine-level/"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Pine Level earned National Register of Historic Places status in 2014, cementing its place as a Florida ghost town.",
